  "prompt": "What happens when one of the twin babies dies in utero?",
  "response": "When one twin dies in utero, this is called \"vanishing twin syndrome\" or \"twin loss.\" The consequences can vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and other factors:\n\n1. Early pregnancy (first trimester):\n- Often, the deceased twin is reabsorbed by the body\n- The surviving twin usually develops normally\n- The mother may not even realize a loss occurred\n\n2. Later pregnancy:\n- The deceased twin may calcify or become compressed\n- Potential risks to the surviving twin include:\n   - Increased chance of cerebral palsy\n   - Higher risk of developmental complications\n   - Potential neurological issues\n\n3. Medical management:\n- Close monitoring of the surviving twin\n- Regular ultrasounds\n- Potential additional medical interventions\n- Possible genetic testing\n\n4. Emotional considerations:\n- Parents may experience grief and emotional complexity\n- Psychological support might be recommended\n\n5. Delivery considerations:\n- Potential need for specialized medical care\n- Possible increased monitoring during labor\n\nThe specific outcomes depend on individual circumstances, timing of loss, and medical intervention. Consulting with a healthcare professional is crucial for personalized guidance.",
